>Anyone using zipstream for os/2? Supposed to be an alternative disk
>compression like stacker...

Yes, I use it now for evaluating. It is NOT like Stacker, that's why I like
it. Stacker compresses by making a large file that emulates a hard disk.
ZipStream assigns a drive letter to a directory, and then zips each file for
itself.

This is done in the background! If you copy 50 files to a ZipStream drive, 
it first copies each file and then, in the background, it starts to zip the
files! This makes file copying much more efficient as it uses idle time to
compress. Doesn't seem to take too much memory, I can comfortably run it on
a 8 MB 486-66.

